{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496998"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:01:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:01:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1453"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1453"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.57,0.02,0.14,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1453"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33653"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1453"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1453"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18989"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"7940"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7934"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8339"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42324"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/33653"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 44-year-old man presents to his general practitioner with a four day history of increasing pain in his left leg. The leg has become reddened, swollen and warm and he feels feverish. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes and a left groin dissection for melanoma three years ago. On examination the changes to his left leg are shown (Image). His blood pressure is 112/82 mmHg, pulse 90/min, 38.2\u02daC and SpO2 99%, on room air. On inspection of the affected limb (pictured), a clearly defined and raised border is evident on the left lower extremity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cellulitis","Erysipelas","Deep vein thrombosis","Lipodermatosclerosis","Contact dermatitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is a clearly defined reddened and raised area on the left leg. This has the appearance of an infective process and the clear demarcation, together with the raised edges points more to a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Eerysipelas\u003C/strong\u003E rather than \u003Cstrong\u003Ecellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E. Cellulitis is less well demarcated than erysipelas as it occurs deeper in the layers of the skin/ subcutaneous tissues. Whilst historically erysipelas has been described on the face, it is now more frequently found on the legs. The most common infecting organisms is usually group A streptococci (GAS). The portal of entry is usually a break in the skin as the result of trauma or an insect bite. The blue area at the distal end of the wound in the photograph suggests a site of trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPredisposing factors to these sorts of infection include immunocompromised states and lymphatic obstruction - both of which could be relevant in this patient, who has diabetes and previous groin lymphatic resection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Edeep vein thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E (DVT) would produce a more generalised swelling of the leg and not be confined to the superficial layers - as in this case. In addition, there are no obvious risk factors for a DVT, such as prolonged stasis of the limbs (e.g. long plane trip, recent surgery or prolonged bed rest).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipodermatosclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic condition, where there is a panniculitis, hardening of the skin and increased redness. The condition usually affects all of both legs and the presence of a unilateral, well defined lesion in this case makes lipodermatosclerosis a\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eless likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContact dermatitis\u003C/strong\u003E presents with erythematous plaques with blisters, oedema, fissures and scaling. It occurs as a result of direct exposure of the skin to an irritant. Given that there is no history of allergy or exposure in the clinical vignette, this option is less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["While erysipelas and cellulitis are similar, erysipelas will commonly present as a well-defined lesion whereas cellulitis will be poorly defined."],"references":["Stanway A. Erysipelas [Internet]. DermNet. 2001 [cited 2023Jan9]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/erysipelas"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18989"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1453"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19482"},{"type":"media","id":"19483"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19482"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b58aa46e-c05b-48ec-85b5-015d671cb805.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b58aa46e-c05b-48ec-85b5-015d671cb805.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"19483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19483"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/37d2829b-a005-4099-b9e7-723bc7423c59.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/37d2829b-a005-4099-b9e7-723bc7423c59.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevi